{
  "doc_id": "3869",
  "text": "Loss of CDX2 may represent a marker of tumor progression in early gastric cancer and carcinomas with an intestinal, but not a non-intestinal phenotype [CITATION_1] . The frequency of ciliated metaplasia differs between intestinal and non-intestinal stomach cancer types [CITATION_2] . For some nations, Lauren type 1 cancer was more common than Lauren type 2 [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Yao [CITATION_5] showed Hispanics differed in Lauren type from other persons. An interaction with between time of diagnosis and Lauren type exists [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . van Beek [CITATION_8] found that Epstein Barr Virus associated cancer was more frequently associated with Lauren type 1 than with Lauren type 2 adenocarcinoma. This study of SEER data found interactions of Lauren type and race, age, and gender to be of such importance that two different regression equations had to be created to describe the data. The importance of separating Lauren types from one another lies in part in the demonstrated multiple interactions between Lauren type and so many other variables, both those found in this study and those found in recent epidemiologic studies.",
